   These CCL based microcontroller platforms boards are increasingly used,
   predominantly in the academia, for sensor networking as well as handling
   complex IoT (Internet of Things) functions. This paper looks into a case
   study of incorporating Arduino and Raspberry Pi for sensor networking,
   data transmission and enabling IoT functionalities. As a practical
   realization, an experimental smart home is realized with an array of
   sensors and a system architecture consisting of a set of Arduino and
   Raspberry Pi modules. The paper presents necessary aspects of codes in
   the form of pseudo-codes and describes some aspects of I/O with respect
   to the sensors used. Finally, the security problems are also addressed.
